any explore whether "one drop" of blood still governs our sense of racial identity, or to what extent contemporary American culture allows for the racially indeterminate individual. Some essays open the scholarly conversation to focus on "ethnic" passers—individuals who complicate the traditional black-white binary—while others explore the slippage between traditional racial passing and related forms of racial performance, including blackface minstrelsy and racial masquerade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx21st century. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPassing (Identity) in literature. 0aPassing (Identity) in motion pictures. 0aPassing (Identity)xHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aPassing (Identity)xHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aPassing (Identity)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPassing (Identity)zUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aRace in literature. 0aRace in motion picturesxUnited States. 0aRace in motion pictures. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aGillespie, Michael B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahan, Lori Harrison‑, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMCCarroll, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendes, Ana Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNegrea, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g